Source: Utica Observer-Dispatch [edited]
<http://www.uticaod.com/archive/2005/06/12/news/30899.html>

Whooping cough worries
----------------------
With 8 cases of whooping cough diagnosed in Oneida County [NY] schools,
parents are learning 1st-hand that immunizations against the disease may
not be enough to prevent onset of the illness. Concerned parents are
likely to hear a troubling message about immunization: officials emphasize
that vaccines given according to recommended guidelines are the most
effective line of defense against contracting communicable illnesses. But
officials caution that the vaccine against whooping cough, also known as
pertussis, may not be 100 percent effective because its effectiveness
declines with [the vaccinee's] age.
"The current vaccine is effective and does protect for a certain amount of
time, up to the age of 7," said Patrice Bogan, director of clinical
services for the Oneida County Health Department. "But we know it wears off
and the situation here proves this."
According to the state Health Department, there have been 241 cases of
whooping cough in Upstate New York in 2005. Whooping cough, an infectious
disease that causes coughing in rapid succession, has affected 14 Oneida
County residents, including 8 students, jarring many parents who already
had their children immunized against the illness.
Bogan points to future vaccines as offering more assurance: Boostrix for
adolescents, and Adacel for age 11-64, currently are being developed and
should be available within a month. Bogan is excited about targeting middle
school students with the new medicine.
"We are eagerly awaiting the new vaccines," she said.
[Byline: Marshand Boone and Beth Seltzer]
