Source: GazetteExtra.com [edited]
<http://www.gazetteextra.com/whoopingcough061305.asp>

Wisconsin led nation in whooping cough cases in 2004
---------------------------------------------------
Public health officials say better monitoring of whooping cough could be
why Wisconsin had the most reports of whooping cough in 2004. The state
had 4048 whooping cough cases in 2004, according to the CDC. New York was
2nd with 2059. Many states had just single- or double-digit figures.
Dan Hopfensperger, director of the Madison-based Wisconsin Immunization
Program, said the state is examining the way it identifies and investigates
cases and is comparing notes with other states. He suspects other states
aren't as aggressive about diagnosing whooping cough, which would skew
statistics.
"As far as discrepancies in the numbers, I don't know that our population
is any more susceptible than the rest of the country. I think it's a lot to
do with case identification and case follow-up," he said. "If you look at
our immunization levels as a whole in the state, we compare very favorably
with the rest of the country."
Hopfensperger also said whooping cough is a cyclical disease, meaning [case
numbers increase and decrease] every 2 to 3 years.
Dr. Matt Hall, a Marshfield Clinic infectious disease specialist,
attributed the state's influx of cases to new testing and more
testing. Wisconsin introduced a new molecular test in the last few years
that "probably doubles the number of cases you can find," Hall said. Other
states may not have the test yet, he said.
--
